05020nam a22007575i 9780823237418DE-B159720230103011142.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230103t20092009nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808232374187 a10.1515/97808232374182doi  a(DE-B1597)554957  a(OCoLC)647876414  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aLIT0000002bisacsh04a810.9/921282732221 aWaldmeir, John C., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCathedrals of Bone :bThe Role of the Body in Contemporary Catholic Literature /cJohn C. Waldmeir. 1aNew York, NY : bFordham University Press, c[2009] 4c©2009  a1 online resource (224 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: The Body, Flesh and Bone -- t1. Discovering the Body: Catholic Literature after Vatican II -- t2. Writing and the Catholic Body: Mary Gordon’s Art -- t3. Preserving the Body: Annie Dillard and Tradition -- t4. Clothing Bodies/Making Priests: The Sacramental Vision of J. F. Powers, Alfred Alcorn, and Louise Erdrich -- t5. The Body in Doubt: Catholic Literature, Theology, and Sexual Abuse -- t6. The Body ‘‘As It Was’’: On the Occasion of Mel Gibson’s The Passion of the Christ -- tConclusion: The Body Mutinies -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe metaphor of the Church as a "body" has shaped Catholic thinking since the Second Vatican Council. Its influence on theological inquiries into Catholic nature and practice is well-known; less obvious is the way it has shaped a generation of Catholic imaginative writers. Cathedrals of Bone is the first full-length study of a cohort of Catholic authors whose art takes seriously the themes of the Council: from novelists such as Mary Gordon, Ron Hansen, Louise Erdrich, and J. F. Powers, to poets such as Annie Dillard, Mary Karr, Lucia Perillo, and Anne Carson, to the Pulitzer Prize-winning playwright John Patrick Shanley. Motivated by the inspirational yet thoroughly incarnational rhetoric of Vatican II, each of these writers encourages readers to think about the human body as a site-perhaps the most important site-of interaction between God and human beings. Although they represent the body in different ways, these late-twentieth-century Catholic artists share a sense of its inherent value. Moreover, they use ideas and terminology from the rich tradition of Catholic sacramentality, especially as it was articulated in the documents of Vatican II, to describe that value. In this way they challenge the Church to take its own tradition seriously and to reconsider its relationship to a relatively recent apologetics that has emphasized a narrow view of human reason and a rigid sense of orthodoxy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 03. Jan 2023) 0aAmerican literaturexCatholic authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aAmerican literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aChristianity and literaturezUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aHuman body in literature. 0aHuman bodyxReligious aspects. 4aCatholic Studies. 4aLiterary Studies. 4aReligion. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014z978311118960408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFordham University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z97831107072980 cprintz978082323060040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780823237418?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823237418423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780823237418/original  a978-3-11-070729-8  Fordham University Press eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-118960-4  Fordham Un